know you're smart and you also know that this 
is, something is wrong here." And then this  

186
00:14:29,480 --> 00:14:32,320
goal of, here's what we need to [inaudible 
00:14:31]. You're like very clear call to action,  

187
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:37,000
almost action item, like leave this meeting 
with, "Let's just be aligned on this thing."

188
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:41,440
Yeah, thanks for calling those out. I hope, and 
again, what I'm trying to convey in my tone is  

189
00:14:41,440 --> 00:14:46,720
also, "You know what? It's Tuesday. We got to 
have this conversation. I'm sure it's going to  

190
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:51,720
end well. I'm not mad." The whole point about 
my manager hates me, right? "I'm not yelling  

191
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:56,360
at you." The more even keeled and even matter 
of fact you can be about something that's kind  

192
00:14:56,360 --> 00:15:03,560
of just run-of-the-mill feedback, the better. And 
I think it's just also what I didn't say before,  

193
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:08,640
and I think it's also important is that, as 
you are recognizing that one of your jobs is  

194
00:15:08,640 --> 00:15:12,680
to give this feedback, is that you have to build 
a relationship with people so they can hear you  

195
00:15:12,680 --> 00:15:21,320
through the lens of, "Oh, Alisa wants to help me." 
Not, "Oh, Alisa hates me. It's always a problem."

196
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:24,560
How did you start that phrase again? Because 
the starting is always the hardest part for me.  

197
00:15:24,560 --> 00:15:27,960
How do you kick off the conversation? 
What was the couple sentences used?

198
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:31,600
I wanted to have a conversation with 
you about some things I've been hearing  

199
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:35,240
from your peers about the way that 
you all are interacting together.

200
00:15:35,240 --> 00:15:40,280
Awesome. So there's an element of, don't 
make it feel like a huge deal. Just like,  

201
00:15:40,280 --> 00:15:42,800
"I want to have this conversation with 
you about something." And it's just like,  

202
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:46,840
"Let's have this conversation and here's what 
we want to leave this conversation with."

203
00:15:46,840 --> 00:15:50,440
Yes. And I can't stress enough that it's 
actually really helpful to also have spent  

204
00:15:50,440 --> 00:15:59,160
some time with Matilda or whoever saying, "Great 
job on the way that project landed." Or, "Hey,  

205
00:15:59,160 --> 00:16:01,760
launches, when they happen 
on time and they're smooth,  

206
00:16:01,760 --> 00:16:04,920
sometimes we don't notice anything. I want 
you to notice, we didn't notice anything.  

207
00:16:04,920 --> 00:16:09,160
That's fantastic. You did a good job in that 
launch," or whatever it is. Because then,  

208
00:16:09,160 --> 00:16:14,880
you've had the conversation with them to give them 
positive feedback and point out what's working,  

209
00:16:14,880 --> 00:16:19,720
that builds the relationship so that you have 
the lens of, "Oh, yeah. When something's working,  

210
00:16:19,720 --> 00:16:23,720
they tell me. When something's not working, they 
tell me, too." That's how you build trust as well.

211
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:25,680
They want to be criticizing them 
[inaudible 00:16:25]. We need to have  

212
00:16:25,680 --> 00:16:28,760
another conversation what we're hearing 
about, problems [inaudible 00:16:28].

213
00:16:28,760 --> 00:16:29,080
Yep.

214
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:31,840
Obviously, if you say it the same way every 
single time, they're going to feel like this  

215
00:16:31,840 --> 00:16:38,240
is weird. Do you recommend it's this kind of Mad 
Libs approach or is it make it your own as much as  

216
00:16:38,240 --> 00:16:42,840
you can? What are kind of the key? Or is it like, 
here's actually how you want to say it every time?

217
00:16:42,840 --> 00:16:48,760
In my book and when I work with my clients, I 
give specific scripts and what I will regularly  

218
00:16:48,760 --> 00:16:53,320
say when I'm working with my clients is, "Okay, so 
this is how I would do it," and then I'll land it  

219
00:16:53,320 --> 00:16:59,760
for them. But they have to make it their own. You 
always have to make it your own and I don't think  

220
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:03,260
it's a problem of doing it the same way every 
time. It's not like people are going to notice  

221
00:17:03,260 --> 00:17:07,560
you because you're talking about different topics, 
theoretically. If you have a formula that can work  

222
00:17:07,560 --> 00:17:12,080
for you, that's going to motivate you to do it, 
that is what's important. And what's important  

223
00:17:12,080 --> 00:17:19,360
is that it's neutral, not loading on or not 
venting on someone and not unloading on someone.

224
00:17:19,360 --> 00:17:23,320
I love that we started with this one because 
it feels like the most common one of just your  

225
00:17:23,320 --> 00:17:27,760
employee is underperforming and you want to 
make sure they understand and adjust. What  

226
00:17:27,760 --> 00:17:31,760
if you're not hearing something from a bunch 
of people? What if it's just your perception  

227
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:39,720
of their writing? You need to work on your 
writing skills or you're coming in late. Is  

228
00:17:39,720 --> 00:17:43,760
there another way you phrase it where it's 
not, "I'm hearing it from other people?"

229
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:51,720
Oh, absolutely. Absolutely. So I'll talk about 
writing. I think it would be something like, okay,  

230
00:17:51,720 --> 00:17:57,200
"Matilda, part of your job is to be able to create 
these documents and I appreciate that you do them  

231
00:17:57,200 --> 00:18:03,920
on time. What I've observed is that they can often 
be not as structured as I'd like them to be and  

232
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:09,240
they also lack a conclusion. So what I'd love you 
to do is look at these three or four examples of  

233
00:18:09,240 --> 00:18:14,520
some folks who are doing them really well and see 
if you can model your writing on theirs. If you  

234
00:18:14,520 --> 00:18:18,920
need to take additional classes or if you need 
help in any way, let me know. But ultimately,  

235
00:18:18,920 --> 00:18:23,440
I want to get your writing to the level where 
everybody is appreciating what you bring to  

236
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:27,660
the table because the level of your writing 
really reflects the level of your thinking."

237
00:18:27,660 --> 00:18:34,280
Mm-hmm. Wow, I like that. I'd want to follow 
your advice if I got that. So the way you  

238
00:18:34,280 --> 00:18:39,560
started that is what I've observed, which 
also is not like, "Here's what I think" or  

239
00:18:39,560 --> 00:18:43,200
"Here's what you just need to do." It's more like, 
"Here's what I've noticed, here's what I've seen,  

240
00:18:43,200 --> 00:18:49,240
here's what I've observed about what you're 
doing." And then it reminds me of, what is it,  

241
00:18:49,240 --> 00:18:53,560
nonviolent communication, that whole 
framework of just focus on what you see,  

242
00:18:53,560 --> 00:18:57,560
not what is wrong with them, 
not what they've done. I guess,  

243
00:18:57,560 --> 00:19:00,680
is there anything there you want to say of 
just the importance of focusing on what you've  

244
00:19:00,680 --> 00:19:05,640
heard from people or what you've observed 
versus maybe what people often do instead?

245
00:19:05,640 --> 00:19:09,360
Yeah, I mean you just really said it and 
I think it's such an important point,  

246
00:19:09,360 --> 00:19:17,720
observable facts. The idea that this is not a 
judgment. This is not... Sort of as less judgy  

247
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:24,080
as possible is also very helpful. It makes it 
neutral. It's observable facts and it's also  

248
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:30,360
sort of based on expectations, right? So the 
writing is, we expect it to be at a certain  

249
00:19:30,360 --> 00:19:35,600
level and it's not that way. And here are the 
reasons it's not, the specific reasons, it's not. 

250
00:19:35,600 --> 00:19:40,720
The way you interact with your peers, it's 
important to be at a certain standard, and here's  

251
00:19:40,720 --> 00:19:44,280
why. Because when we all work together, we're 
going to be able to execute and when we don't,  

252
00:19:44,280 --> 00:19:49,680
unfortunately we won't be able to. So you staying 
in sync with them is important and the observation  

253
00:19:49,680 --> 00:19:54,840
is that they don't feel fully in sync with you.
And so every time we talk about this, it doesn't  

254
00:19:54,840 --> 00:19:59,520
become this, "Oh, I don't know. I just feel..." 
By the way, some things you have to give feedback  

255
00:19:59,520 --> 00:20:05,440
on and they are kind of a feeling and those are 
more difficult, but so many things if you do the  

256
00:20:05,440 --> 00:20:12,360
work to really think about what is the observable 
data, I always ask my clients, what's my evidence  

257
00:20:12,360 --> 00:20:16,240
that this is happening? And you have to spend 
some time thinking about it, but it's really  

258
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:20,720
worth it because it makes the feedback easier 
for you to give and easier for them to hear.

259
00:20:20,720 --> 00:20:24,200
Is there anything else along the lines 
of this specific type of feedback that  

260
00:20:24,200 --> 00:20:28,640
is worth sharing before we move on 
to a different type of feedback?

261
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:34,480
Well, I think just that the reason, one of the 
many reasons that people have gone uncomfortable  

262
00:20:34,480 --> 00:20:37,960
giving feedback is that somebody might 
get defensive or they might start crying  

263
00:20:37,960 --> 00:20:42,960
as we talked about. And so I have a script 
also, which is if someone gets defensive,  

264
00:20:42,960 --> 00:20:47,760
which is it's like I'm giving you this feedback 
and you're getting defensive and I say, "Well,  

265
00:20:47,760 --> 00:20:53,360
let's pause for a second. First of all, I want 
you to know that I'm telling you this actually,  

266
00:20:53,360 --> 00:20:57,080
just to make you better because I know how 
important your career is to you. I know how  

267
00:20:57,080 --> 00:21:01,840
important the success is to you and it's important 
to me too as your leader. The second thing is,  

268
00:21:01,840 --> 00:21:06,840
my observation is that you're getting a little 
bit emotional. I want to know if we can continue  

269
00:21:06,840 --> 00:21:11,360
having this conversation now or if we need to 
kind of pause it. At the end of the day, we  

270
00:21:11,360 --> 00:21:15,440
really have to have this conversation and I really 
want to see you make changes, but I understand  

271
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:22,320
you might need a few moments to digest it."
The importance of that for you is not even what  

272
00:21:22,320 --> 00:21:28,520
you say, but that you have prepared and you are 
prepared for if someone has that kind of reaction  

273
00:21:29,160 --> 00:21:34,080
and that you don't have to, yourself, react to 
it. You know, "No, I'm not doing that. No, no,  

274
00:21:34,080 --> 00:21:38,840
no, no, whatever." And you can say, "Yes, you 
are." Now we're in a fight and that is not cool  

275
00:21:38,840 --> 00:21:43,640
for anybody. It's certainly not cool for you 
as a leader. So it gives you the opportunity  

276
00:21:43,640 --> 00:21:48,280
to recognize that you have another tool 
in your toolkit rather than just react.

277
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:53,080
So if you find yourself feeling 
defensive or they are just not  

278
00:21:53,080 --> 00:21:58,920
hearing and just fighting back, the tool is 
just pause. Let's just pause for a moment  

279
00:21:58,920 --> 00:22:02,200
and it feels like there's kind of two 
parts to which you just shared. One is,  

280
00:22:02,200 --> 00:22:08,960
remind them why this is important to them and 
why you're talking about this. And then two is,  

281
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:14,400
if there's just emotions kind of taking over, 
give them a chance to like, "Let's just pause  

282
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:19,000
and maybe come back to this because maybe you're 
not in the right state right now to listen."

283
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:20,840
Yeah, exactly.

284
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:24,920
Sometimes people get upset when you mention like, 
"You're getting emotional," or I don't know. Is  

285
00:22:24,920 --> 00:22:29,476
that a thing that you deal with of just like, "How 
dare you say I'm feeling emotional?" I'm just...

286
00:22:29,476 --> 00:22:31,920
I'm not emotional. Why do you think 
[inaudible 00:22:31] emotional? Right,  

287
00:22:31,920 --> 00:22:37,040
exactly. Yes, of course. Now, when someone's 
crying, they're obviously getting emotional.  

288
00:22:37,040 --> 00:22:41,600
When they're defensive, it's possible that 
you might want to use a different word. I  

289
00:22:41,600 --> 00:22:46,240
can see that this is really upsetting 
you or this is really triggering you,  

290
00:22:46,240 --> 00:22:51,360
or I can see that the temperature between 
us has just changed. You could say something  

291
00:22:51,360 --> 00:22:56,560
like that. I do think also it's helpful 
to know your people because sometimes you  

292
00:22:56,560 --> 00:22:59,720
could realize that actually they can deal 
with that, but then sometimes you have to  

293
00:22:59,720 --> 00:23:05,520
really [inaudible 00:23:00] the delicate words 
that you need to use to pause the conversation.

294
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:10,960
Yeah. And I find, to your point, it's helpful 
to you too as the person giving it. And I feel  

295
00:23:10,960 --> 00:23:16,840
like sometimes, you may be feeling like I should 
just pull back and maybe I'm wrong, maybe they're  

296
00:23:16,840 --> 00:23:22,600
right, maybe I should stop and instead this gives 
you a chance to know I'm actually, I can't. I need  

297
00:23:22,600 --> 00:23:26,480
to stay strong about what I believe because 
I... You put so much thought and effort into  

298
00:23:26,480 --> 00:23:30,840
this already, it's unlikely you're just like, 
oh, totally wrong about what you're saying.

299
00:23:30,840 --> 00:23:33,920
Yeah, exactly. There's something going on. 
There's something going on. And then also,  

300
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:37,680
the whole point about it being a conversation 
is that actually it's a conversation. Actually,  

301
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:39,040
Lenny, if you have a different point of view,  

302
00:23:39,040 --> 00:23:43,200
I would like to hear it. Let's talk about 
it, but we can't keep going on like this,  

303
00:23:43,200 --> 00:23:48,120
where I don't feel I can count on you for 
whatever it is that we're talking about. So  

304
00:23:48,120 --> 00:23:53,040
we need to have this conversation and recreate a 
set of expectations between ourselves. Ultimately,  

305
00:23:53,040 --> 00:23:57,800
that kind of conversation has the potential to 
really build the relationship and build trust,  

306
00:23:57,800 --> 00:24:04,240
and that's another reason I encourage everybody to 
get over their discomfort and to lean into having  

307
00:24:04,240 --> 00:24:09,680
these conversations because on the other side 
of that, is a much better, stronger connection.

308
00:24:09,680 --> 00:24:11,920
And especially if you do them well.

309
00:24:11,920 --> 00:24:12,320
Yes.

310
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:18,800
Following this advice. So okay, so again, if 
somebody's feeling defensive, can you again say  

311
00:24:18,800 --> 00:24:25,760
how you start that, if you notice that? And then 
I'll highlight the two elements again of the...

312
00:24:25,760 --> 00:24:31,560
So the way to pause is to actually say, 
"Let's just pause for a second because  

313
00:24:31,560 --> 00:24:36,000
I'm feeling the energy has changed and I can 
see that you're getting a little bit heated  

314
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:41,360
by what I'm saying and I want you to know that I 
have no intention of upsetting you. I just want  

315
00:24:41,360 --> 00:24:45,600
to be able to talk to you about the things 
that are going to help you in your career."

316
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:50,960
Awesome. And I love, again, just the reminder 
of here's why this is important to you,  

317
00:24:50,960 --> 00:24:55,280
here's the benefit to you and why this will help 
you. And then it's like, "Okay, let's just maybe  

318
00:24:55,280 --> 00:24:58,320
take a pause and come back to this conversation 
if you're feeling like this isn't the best time."  

319
00:24:59,040 --> 00:25:02,360
Awesome. Anything else along that line before 
we go to another type of a hard conversation?

320
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:08,000
I mean, I can talk all day about this 
[inaudible 00:25:06], but I'm happy to move on.

321
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,360
Well, let's pick another topic. I know 
you have kind of five buckets and types  

322
00:25:11,360 --> 00:25:14,880
of conversation. Maybe the promotion one. 
That feels like I think we're in performance  

323
00:25:14,880 --> 00:25:18,400
review season. It feels like these are 
happening a bunch. What do you suggest  

324
00:25:18,400 --> 00:25:23,440
when someone's being told they're not going 
to get the promotion they expected or wanted?

325
00:25:24,040 --> 00:25:27,800
Of course that's challenging. So again, 
getting your mindset right, recognizing they're  

326
00:25:27,800 --> 00:25:31,760
disappointed, they're going to be disappointed, 
recognizing how you felt, the time that when you  

327
00:25:31,760 --> 00:25:36,600
didn't get a promotion or whatever. And so kind 
of coming to it with some compassion. And also,  

328
00:25:36,600 --> 00:25:39,800
you have to get your reasoning right. So sometimes 
people think they should get a promotion because  

329
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:43,440
they were here for a year or whatever. Sometimes 
people think they should get a promotion because  

330
00:25:43,440 --> 00:25:48,040
they're the only internal candidate who's 
qualified for this or they might have a sense  

331
00:25:48,040 --> 00:25:55,040
of themselves succeeding or achieving that is more 
inflated maybe than you see them. So trying to  

332
00:25:55,040 --> 00:25:58,240
think about where they're coming from.
And then the conversation is just,  

333
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,520
"Matilda, I know this is going to be challenging 
for you to hear. I know you were hoping to get  

334
00:26:03,520 --> 00:26:08,120
that promotion, but I want to let you know that we 
are going to actually be looking for an external  

335
00:26:08,120 --> 00:26:13,160
candidate. I want to give you a few thoughts 
about why. First of all, in discussing this with  

336
00:26:13,160 --> 00:26:19,800
my peers, I'm realizing that we need someone 
who has done this role multiple times in the  

337
00:26:19,800 --> 00:26:25,440
past and has that experience. Number two, I think 
it's really important that they have an expertise  

338
00:26:25,440 --> 00:26:31,280
in a specific realm that we've identified 
as really important. So for those reasons,  

339
00:26:31,280 --> 00:26:34,160
we're going to bring someone in from 
the outside, not going to promote you,  

340
00:26:34,160 --> 00:26:38,440
but I want you to know this. Number one, 
it's really important to me that you're able  

341
00:26:38,440 --> 00:26:43,080
to succeed in your career here. And so I want 
to continue to help you find opportunities to  

342
00:26:43,080 --> 00:26:49,120
build your skills and to advance. And then number 
two, when we bring this person in, I'm committed  

343
00:26:49,120 --> 00:26:53,800
to finding someone who's a great people leader, 
who is going to help you build those skills."

344
00:26:53,800 --> 00:26:58,400
So a few elements there that stood out to 
me. One is just being very upfront and not  

345
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:03,680
bearing the lead. Telling them very early, 
"Here's what I've decided." As you said it,  

346
00:27:03,680 --> 00:27:09,600
I could see my heart sinking immediately when I 
feel that. So at least that's over and then it's,  

347
00:27:09,600 --> 00:27:13,000
here's why. And that starts 
to help you feel like, "Okay,  

348
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:16,360
I get it. I understand at least how you 
thought about this." And then there's the  

349
00:27:16,360 --> 00:27:21,320
hope for the future, your painting of, 
here's how I can get there eventually.

350
00:27:21,320 --> 00:27:26,280
Yes, that hope for the future is so important 
and I think sometimes we're such in a rush  

351
00:27:26,280 --> 00:27:30,400
to kind of deliver the bad news that we forget 
there's a human being over there who needs hope  

352
00:27:30,400 --> 00:27:36,360
for the future. And hopefully. If they're a good 
employee, hopefully they have hope for the future.

353
00:27:36,360 --> 00:27:38,480
I love that. Is there anything 
else to that script that you  

354
00:27:38,480 --> 00:27:41,560
think is really highlighting or do you 
think I touched on the key elements?

355
00:27:41,560 --> 00:27:43,000
I think you touched on the key elements.

356
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:44,840
Okay. And again, the way you started is,  

357
00:27:44,840 --> 00:27:48,240
I have some bad news for you or I 
have some disappointing news for you.

358
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:49,675
Yes, because it's just [inaudible 00:27:50].

359
00:27:49,675 --> 00:27:50,520
Just get right into it. Yeah.

360
00:27:50,520 --> 00:27:54,480
Yeah, just get right into it. Yeah. By 
the way, the other piece on that might be,  

361
00:27:54,480 --> 00:27:59,480
if it's appropriate, I'd love you to digest this 
information and then let's talk about it again  

362
00:27:59,480 --> 00:28:04,200
next week to see what you've come up with or see 
how you feel about it because you want to send,  

363
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:09,080
this is not the script, this is for me to you. 
You want to send the, I care about you message  

364
00:28:09,080 --> 00:28:16,040
because that's the other thing. In the workplace, 
people, they're going through all their feelings,  

365
00:28:16,040 --> 00:28:19,760
all their emotions, disappointments. They're 
going to go home and tell their spouse,  

366
00:28:19,760 --> 00:28:24,680
didn't get the promotion or whatever. It's going 
to loom large. It's going to be demoralizing. 

367
00:28:24,680 --> 00:28:30,360
When you, as a leader signal a lot, I care 
about you, I care about your feelings,  

